    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Definitely an awesome video to understand where your issue comes from!\r\nThis is actually concerning `autocomplete.js`, not `instantsearch.js`, but indeed, let's keep it simple and answer here. [Let's just make sure to not keep this issue opened for too long]\r\n\r\nThe idea with `autocomplete.js` is that indeed, it will close automatically on loss of focus. This is intended, as this is the behavior we want most of the time.\r\nMobile keyboards are indeed an issue, but most of the time, you can still scroll the results list and find what you want.\r\nI don't believe there's any way to detect a specific \"close keyboard\" event.\r\n\r\nYou basically got it right with\r\n> The issue might be due to the fact, that when you dismiss the keybord in iOS, it removes focus from the input field/search form.\r\n\r\nHowever, in your case, the cool thing is that I believe it's fairly easy to fix.\r\nIndeed, you have an overlay when you click on search. We can exploit it to have the autocomplete only close when the overlay is clicked.\r\nThe easiest solution I see for this would be this one:\r\n1. Activate the debug mode of the autocomplete in our Shopify app\r\n   This will prevent the autocomplete from closing when the input loses focus\r\n2. In `algolia_autocomplete.js.liquid`, replace the `appendTo: 'body'` by your overlay: `appendTo: '.waikiki-search > .search-content'`. If I'm not mistaken, when your overlay hides, then the autocomplete should hide at the same time.",
